First, let's tackle the dfs function. Let me look at the Java method:

public static boolean dfs(int currpos, int[] arr, int target) {

The Fortran equivalent would be a FUNCTION that returns a logical, takes currpos (integer), arr (integer array), target (integer).

Wait, but currpos must be less than or equal to n. Because if currpos is beyond n, then we return false. Wait, the Java code condition is:

if (currpos == target) return true;

if (currpos == arr.length +1) return false;

The arr.length is n-1. So in Java, when currpos is (n-1) +1), which is n, the function returns false. Wait. So, in Fortran, the code:

if (currpos == target) => return true. if (currpos == (size(arr) + 1)) => return false.

Let me see the detailed Java code: The code in the Java's dfs:

if currpos == target → true. if currpos == (arr.length +1) → false. teleport = dfs(currpos + arr[currpos-1], arr, target);

 if (teleport) return true. return false.
